    <figure>
      <img class="img-responsive" src="assets/rebioinc_process_02.jpg">
      <figcaption>
       The first process in our system turns the sugar biomass into fuel-grade ethanol. Fuel-grade ethanol is 99.9% alcohol (198 proof), and our gasoline supply currently has 10% ethanol blended into it already. Almost identical to the process for making drinkable spirits, ethanol is made by fermenting organic material and distillation. The main difference is the removal of all excess water.
     </figcaption>
     <figcaption>
      The University of California at Davis conducted a research project last year showing that grape pomace can be turned into fuel-grade ethanol. To view their white paper click here...
    </figcaption>
    <figcaption>
     Ethanol is pure alcohol, which drastically reduces tailpipe emissions. In fact, you may have seen placards next to the gas pump that say “Up to 10% of the gasoline purchased at this pump is fuel-grade ethanol.” The EPA has recently approved a 15% ethanol blend in all gasoline, which means demand for ethanol is going to rise significantly in the coming years. Most of the ethanol consumed in California is produced in the Midwest and shipped by rail. The growth of fuel crops, and transportation of fuel once it is produced comes with its own set of ethical implications. The ethanol we are producing is created from local and regional waste streams, and consumed locally.
