  </figcaption> <figcaption>
  Gasification is an industrial process that takes organic waste and burns it with a very low presence of oxygen. This does a few things: 1) it produces a flammable gas called syngas (no smoke); 2) it sequesters all the remaining carbon in the form of a charcoal-like substance called Biochar, and; 3) it creates a lot of heat. The syngas is used to fire an internal combustion engine to make electricity (generator set). The Biochar is used as a high-grade soil amendment. The heat is used to make ethanol, as well as off-set the thermal needs of other on-site facilities.
</figcaption>
</figure>

